# View Component Review Checklist

After creating or modifying a view component, run through every section below. Fix all issues before considering the component complete.

---

## 1. File Structure Completeness

Verify ALL required files exist under `view-components/<component-name>/`:

- [ ] `<name>.types.ts` — shared property interfaces
- [ ] `<name>-registration.module.ts` — platform registration
- [ ] `design/<name>-design.component.ts` — design-time component class
- [ ] `design/<name>-design.component.html` — design-time template
- [ ] `design/<name>-design.component.scss` — design-time styles
- [ ] `design/<name>-design.model.ts` — design model (inspector + validation)
- [ ] `design/<name>-design.types.ts` — design-time property interface
- [ ] `runtime/<name>.component.ts` — runtime component class
- [ ] `runtime/<name>.component.html` — runtime template
- [ ] `runtime/<name>.component.scss` — runtime styles

**Red flag**: Missing any file means the component will fail at design-time or runtime.

---

## 2. Types File (`<name>.types.ts`)

- [ ] Interface extends `IRxStandardProps` from `@helix/platform/view/api`
- [ ] `name: string` property is present (required for component identification in View Designer)
- [ ] All custom properties that appear in the inspector are declared here
- [ ] Property types are specific (avoid `any` — use `string`, `number`, `boolean`, etc.)

```typescript
// CORRECT
import { IRxStandardProps } from '@helix/platform/view/api';
export interface IMyComponentProperties extends IRxStandardProps {
  name: string;
  title: string;
  // ... all custom properties
}
```

**Red flag**: If a property is used in runtime/design but not declared in the interface, TypeScript safety is lost.

---

## 3. Registration Module (`<name>-registration.module.ts`)

- [ ] Decorated with `@NgModule()`
- [ ] Constructor injects `RxViewComponentRegistryService`
- [ ] `type` follows exact naming convention: `com-mycompany-sample-app-com-mycompany-sample-app-<kebab-name>`
- [ ] `name` is a human-readable display name
- [ ] `group` is set (e.g., `'Sample App'`)
- [ ] `icon` is set to a valid icon name
- [ ] `component` references the **runtime** component class
- [ ] `designComponent` references the **design** component class
- [ ] `designComponentModel` references the **design model** class
- [ ] `properties` array includes ALL custom properties as objects with `name`, `localizable`, `enableExpressionEvaluation`
- [ ] `properties` array spreads `...RX_STANDARD_PROPS_DESC` at the end
- [ ] `RX_STANDARD_PROPS_DESC` is imported from `@helix/platform/view/api`

```typescript
// CORRECT — verify type name matches runtime @RxViewComponent name and selector
rxViewComponentRegistryService.register({
  type: 'com-mycompany-sample-app-com-mycompany-sample-app-calculator',
  name: 'Calculator',
  group: 'Sample App',
  icon: 'calculator',
  component: CalculatorComponent,
  designComponent: CalculatorDesignComponent,
  designComponentModel: CalculatorDesignModel,
  properties: [
    { name: 'title', localizable: true, enableExpressionEvaluation: true },
    ...RX_STANDARD_PROPS_DESC
  ]
});
```

**Cross-check**: The `type` value here MUST exactly match the `name` in `@RxViewComponent()` decorator on the runtime component AND the runtime component's `selector`.

---

## 4. Design Model (`design/<name>-design.model.ts`)

### Class Declaration
- [ ] Extends `ViewDesignerComponentModel<IProperties, IDesignProperties>`
- [ ] Implements `IViewDesignerComponentModel<IProperties, IDesignProperties>`
- [ ] Constructor signature: `constructor(protected injector: Injector, protected sandbox: IViewComponentDesignSandbox<IDesignProperties>)`
- [ ] Calls `super(injector, sandbox)` first in constructor

### Inspector Configuration
- [ ] Calls `sandbox.updateInspectorConfig(this.setInspectorConfig(...))` in constructor
- [ ] `setInspectorConfig` returns `inspectorSectionConfigs` array with labeled sections
- [ ] Every custom property has a matching control in the inspector config
- [ ] Control `name` values exactly match property names in the types interface
- [ ] Ends with `...getStandardPropsInspectorConfigs()` to include Hidden, CSS classes, etc.
- [ ] Uses correct form control components (`TextFormControlComponent`, `SwitchFormControlComponent`, etc.)
- [ ] Each control has `label` and `tooltip` (use `new Tooltip('...')` from `@helix/platform/shared/api`)

### Validation
- [ ] Subscribes to `sandbox.componentProperties$` for validation
- [ ] Subscription uses `takeUntil(this.sandbox.destroyed$)` to prevent memory leaks
- [ ] `validate` method calls `validateStandardProps(model)` and returns its issues
- [ ] Custom validations added to the `validationIssues` array as needed

### Static `getInitialProperties` Method
- [ ] Method exists and is `static`
- [ ] Returns object spreading `RX_STANDARD_PROPS_DEFAULT_VALUES`
- [ ] Sets sensible defaults for all custom properties
- [ ] Spreads `...currentProperties` last (so saved values override defaults)

```typescript
static getInitialProperties(currentProperties?: IMyProperties): IMyDesignProperties {
  return {
    name: '',
    title: 'Default Title',
    ...RX_STANDARD_PROPS_DEFAULT_VALUES,
    ...currentProperties
  };
}
```

### Data Dictionary
- [ ] Subscribes to `sandbox.getComponentPropertyValue('name')` for dynamic naming
- [ ] Calls `sandbox.setSettablePropertiesDataDictionary(...)` with all Set-property-able fields
- [ ] Calls `sandbox.setCommonDataDictionary(...)` with all expression-readable fields
- [ ] Uses `this.getExpressionForProperty('propName')` for each entry

**Red flag**: If a property is in the inspector but not in `getSettablePropertiesDataDictionary`, it cannot be set via "Set Property" action at runtime.

---

## 5. Design Component (`design/<name>-design.component.ts`)

- [ ] `standalone: true`
- [ ] Selector follows convention: `com-mycompany-sample-app-com-mycompany-sample-app-<name>-design`
- [ ] Has `@Input() model: <Name>DesignModel` — typed to the specific design model class
- [ ] `templateUrl` and `styleUrls` point to correct files
- [ ] Template shows a meaningful preview (not just empty div)
- [ ] Preview uses dashed border and muted colors to distinguish from runtime

---

## 6. Design Types (`design/<name>-design.types.ts`)

- [ ] Interface extends the main component properties interface: `extends IMyComponentProperties`
- [ ] Add any design-only properties here (properties needed only at design-time)
- [ ] Exported so the design model can import it

```typescript
import { IMyComponentProperties } from '../my-component.types';
export interface IMyComponentDesignProperties extends IMyComponentProperties {
  // design-only properties if any
}
```

---

## 7. Runtime Component (`runtime/<name>.component.ts`)

### Class Setup
- [ ] `standalone: true`
- [ ] `imports` array includes `CommonModule` and any other needed modules (`FormsModule`, etc.)
- [ ] Selector: `com-mycompany-sample-app-com-mycompany-sample-app-<name>` (NO `-design` suffix)
- [ ] `@RxViewComponent({ name: '...' })` decorator present — name MUST match registration `type`
- [ ] Extends `BaseViewComponent`
- [ ] Implements `OnInit` and `IViewComponent`
- [ ] `@Input() config: Observable<IMyComponentProperties>` — Observable, not plain object

### Lifecycle
- [ ] `ngOnInit()` calls `super.ngOnInit()` first
- [ ] `notifyPropertyChanged('api', this.api)` called in `ngOnInit` to expose API
- [ ] Config subscription uses `distinctUntilChanged()` and `takeUntil(this.destroyed$)`
- [ ] Sets `this.isHidden = Boolean(config.hidden)` inside config subscription

### API Object
- [ ] `api` object defined with `setProperty: this.setProperty.bind(this)`
- [ ] Any additional public methods added to `api` and `.bind(this)`-ed
- [ ] `setProperty` handles each settable property in a `switch` statement
- [ ] Each case calls `this.notifyPropertyChanged(propertyPath, propertyValue)`
- [ ] Default case returns `throwError(...)` for unknown properties

```typescript
private setProperty(propertyPath: string, propertyValue: any): void | Observable<never> {
  switch (propertyPath) {
    case 'hidden':
      this.state.hidden = propertyValue;
      this.notifyPropertyChanged(propertyPath, propertyValue);
      break;
    case 'title':
      this.state.title = propertyValue;
      this.notifyPropertyChanged(propertyPath, propertyValue);
      break;
    default:
      return throwError(`MyComponent: property ${propertyPath} is not settable.`);
  }
}
```

### Imports Verification
- [ ] `BaseViewComponent` from `@helix/platform/view/runtime`
- [ ] `IViewComponent` from `@helix/platform/view/runtime`
- [ ] `RxViewComponent` from `@helix/platform/view/api`
- [ ] `Observable, throwError` from `rxjs`
- [ ] `distinctUntilChanged, takeUntil` from `rxjs/operators`

---

## 8. Runtime Template (`runtime/<name>.component.html`)

- [ ] No unescaped `@` characters — use `&#64;` (Angular interprets `@` as control flow)
- [ ] All event bindings use `(click)`, `(input)`, etc. — not `on-click`
- [ ] `*ngIf` / `*ngFor` used correctly (or `@if` / `@for` with proper Angular 17+ syntax)
- [ ] Component state accessed via `state?.property` with safe navigation
- [ ] No direct DOM manipulation — use Angular bindings

---

## 9. Runtime Styles (`runtime/<name>.component.scss`)

- [ ] Styles scoped to a container class (avoid bare element selectors leaking globally)
- [ ] No hardcoded colors that conflict with platform themes (prefer CSS variables when possible)
- [ ] Responsive considerations for different device sizes

---

## 10. Main Module Integration

**File**: `libs/com-mycompany-sample-app/src/lib/com-mycompany-sample-app.module.ts`

- [ ] Registration module is imported: `import { <Name>RegistrationModule } from './view-components/<name>/<name>-registration.module';`
- [ ] Registration module is added to the `imports` array in `@NgModule`

---

## 11. Index.ts Export

**File**: `libs/com-mycompany-sample-app/src/index.ts`

- [ ] Registration module is exported: `export * from './lib/view-components/<name>/<name>-registration.module';`

**Red flag**: Missing this export means the component won't be bundled into the build output.

---

## 12. Cross-File Consistency (Critical)

These values MUST be identical across files — a mismatch causes silent failures:

| Value | Where It Appears |
|-------|-----------------|
| Component type string | Registration `type`, Runtime `@RxViewComponent({ name })`, Runtime `selector` |
| Properties interface | Types file, Design model generics, Runtime `config` type |
| Design properties interface | Design types file, Design model generics |
| Custom property names | Types interface, Registration `properties[].name`, Design model inspector `controls[].name`, Design model `getInitialProperties`, Runtime `setProperty` switch cases |
| Design model class | Registration `designComponentModel`, Design component `@Input() model` type |

Run this cross-check:
1. Grep for the component type string — it must appear exactly in registration, `@RxViewComponent`, and selector.
2. For each property in the types interface, verify it has: an inspector control, an initial value, a `setProperty` case (if settable), and a data dictionary entry (if expression-readable).

---

## 13. Module Federation & AOT Compilation Pitfalls

### Module Federation Naming

- [ ] Component names are compatible with lodash `camelCase` behavior — Module Federation transforms module names using `camelCase`, which can mangle unexpected characters
- [ ] Verify the component name in the compiled output matches what View Designer expects — mismatches cause silent load failures
- [ ] Stick to simple kebab-case names (letters and hyphens only) to avoid camelCase transformation surprises

### AOT Compilation Issues

The most common first-component failure is `ɵmod undefined` — the component doesn't show in the View Designer palette even though the build succeeds. This is caused by AOT compilation not processing the registration module correctly.

**Resolution sequence** (may require up to 3 iterations):

1. **AOT compatibility**: Ensure all decorators (`@NgModule`, `@Component`) use static metadata — no function calls or computed values in decorator arguments
2. **Module naming**: Verify the registration module class name exactly matches the import in `com-mycompany-sample-app.module.ts` — AOT resolves by class name, not file path
3. **Registration wiring**: Confirm the registration module is both imported in `@NgModule({ imports: [...] })` AND exported in `index.ts` — missing either one causes the AOT compiler to tree-shake it out

- [ ] After first component build, check browser console for `ɵmod` errors — if present, work through the 3-step sequence above
- [ ] All subsequent components (after the first one works) should work on first try if they follow the same pattern

### Incremental Component Development Strategy

Based on real-world experience: the first component takes multiple iterations to get right; subsequent components work on first try.

- [ ] **Build and deploy the FIRST component before generating any others** — resolve all platform quirks on one component
- [ ] Only after the first component renders correctly in View Designer AND at runtime, generate remaining components using the proven pattern
- [ ] All components should follow the exact same 10-file structure — AI-generated components maintain perfect consistency when generated from the same learned pattern
- [ ] Verify each batch of new components in View Designer before proceeding to the next batch

---

## 14. Common Mistakes to Catch

- **Wrong selector on runtime vs design**: Runtime has NO `-design` suffix; design component DOES.
- **Forgetting `super.ngOnInit()`**: Breaks `BaseViewComponent` lifecycle; `destroyed$` won't work.
- **Missing `...RX_STANDARD_PROPS_DESC`**: Hidden, CSS classes, and device visibility won't work.
- **Missing `...RX_STANDARD_PROPS_DEFAULT_VALUES`**: Standard props reset to undefined on load.
- **Missing `...getStandardPropsInspectorConfigs()`**: Hidden toggle won't appear in property inspector.
- **Missing `validateStandardProps(model)`**: Standard property validation bypassed.
- **Subscription without `takeUntil`**: Memory leak — component never unsubscribes.
- **`setProperty` missing `notifyPropertyChanged`**: Property updates via actions silently fail.
- **Inspector control `name` typo**: Property appears in inspector but never binds to the actual value.
- **Forgetting to spread `...currentProperties`** in `getInitialProperties`: Saved view values are lost on reload.
- **Unescaped `@` in templates**: Angular 17+ interprets `@` as control flow syntax — use `&#64;` for literal `@` (e.g., email addresses). Error message: `Incomplete block "example". If you meant to write the @ character...`
- **Over-engineering**: AI tends to generate "complete" solutions upfront (pagination, queue processing, status services) that may not be needed. Start simpler and add complexity incrementally.

---

## 15. Pre-Build Verification

Before running the build, confirm these prerequisites:

- [ ] All TypeScript files compile without errors — run `npx tsc --noEmit` or check IDE for red underlines
- [ ] No circular dependency between component files (types -> design -> runtime -> types)
- [ ] All imports resolve — no `Module not found` in the IDE
- [ ] If component uses `HttpClient`, verify `HttpClientModule` or `provideHttpClient()` is available
- [ ] If component uses `FormsModule` or `ReactiveFormsModule`, it is in the standalone `imports` array

### Docker Host-to-Container File Sync Verification (Critical)

When developing on the host and building inside Docker, the bind mount (`./workspace:/workspace`) can have **stale file sync** — newly created files appear inside the container, but edits to existing files may NOT propagate. This causes a deceptive failure: the build succeeds, the manifest lists the component, but the compiled JS bundles are missing it.

**Always verify these files match between host and container after editing:**

```bash
# Compare index.ts
docker exec bmc-helix-innovation-studio bash -c "cat /workspace/sample-app/bundle/src/main/webapp/libs/com-mycompany-sample-app/src/index.ts"

# Compare main module
docker exec bmc-helix-innovation-studio bash -c "cat /workspace/sample-app/bundle/src/main/webapp/libs/com-mycompany-sample-app/src/lib/com-mycompany-sample-app.module.ts"
```

- [ ] `index.ts` inside the container contains the new component's `export *` line
- [ ] `com-mycompany-sample-app.module.ts` inside the container contains the new registration module import AND it appears in the `imports` array

**If files are out of sync**, apply the edits directly inside the container:

```bash
# Add export to index.ts
docker exec bmc-helix-innovation-studio bash -c "echo 'export * from \"./lib/view-components/<name>/<name>-registration.module\";' >> /workspace/sample-app/bundle/src/main/webapp/libs/com-mycompany-sample-app/src/index.ts"

# Add import and NgModule entry to main module (use sed or write the full file)
docker exec bmc-helix-innovation-studio bash -c "sed -i 's|import { PreviousModule }|import { PreviousModule }\nimport { NewModule }|' ..."
```

**Red flag**: If the build output chunk sizes are the SAME as the previous build (before adding your component), the new component code was NOT compiled in — the container is using stale source files.

---

## 16. Post-Build Checks

### Frontend Build (`npm run build`)

```bash
docker exec bmc-helix-innovation-studio bash -c "cd /workspace/sample-app/bundle/src/main/webapp && npm run build"
```

- [ ] Build completes with exit code 0 — no errors in output
- [ ] No TypeScript compilation errors (`error TS****`)
- [ ] No Angular template errors (`error NG****`)
- [ ] No "Module not found" or "Cannot resolve" errors
- [ ] No circular dependency warnings (`Circular dependency detected`)
- [ ] Build output directory exists: `dist/apps/shell/`

### Manifest Verification

**File**: `dist/apps/shell/com-mycompany-sample-app.json`

- [ ] File exists and is valid JSON
- [ ] `viewComponents` array includes the new component type string: `com-mycompany-sample-app-com-mycompany-sample-app-<name>`
- [ ] No duplicate entries in the `viewComponents` array

```bash
# Quick verification — component should appear in manifest
docker exec bmc-helix-innovation-studio bash -c "cat /workspace/sample-app/bundle/src/main/webapp/dist/apps/shell/com-mycompany-sample-app.json | python3 -m json.tool"
```

**Red flag**: If the component type is missing from the manifest, the platform will never load it — even if all source files are correct.

### Compiled JS Bundle Verification (Critical)

The manifest can list a component even when it's NOT in the compiled JS. This happens when the manifest generator scans the filesystem (sees the registration file) but the TypeScript compiler uses a stale `index.ts` or main module that doesn't import it. **Always verify the component type string exists in the actual JS chunks.**

```bash
# Verify component type string exists in the compiled JS bundles
docker exec bmc-helix-innovation-studio bash -c "grep -c '<component-type-string>' /workspace/sample-app/bundle/src/main/webapp/dist/apps/shell/libs_com-mycompany-sample-app_src_index_ts*.js"
```

- [ ] Component type string appears in the lazy chunk JS files (count > 0)
- [ ] Both the runtime selector (`<name>`) and design selector (`<name>-design`) appear in the chunks
- [ ] Lazy chunk file sizes are **larger** than the previous build (the new component code adds ~5-50KB)

```bash
# Full verification — list all registered component type strings in the build output
docker exec bmc-helix-innovation-studio bash -c "grep -o 'com-mycompany-sample-app-com-mycompany-sample-app-[a-z-]*' /workspace/sample-app/bundle/src/main/webapp/dist/apps/shell/libs_com-mycompany-sample-app_src_index_ts*.js | sort -u"
```

**Red flag**: If the component appears in the manifest JSON but NOT in the grep output above, the `index.ts` or main module inside the Docker container is stale. See Section 15 "Docker Host-to-Container File Sync Verification" to fix.

### Full Maven Build (`mvn clean install`)

```bash
docker exec bmc-helix-innovation-studio bash -c "cd /workspace/sample-app && mvn clean install -DskipTests"
```

- [ ] Maven build completes with `BUILD SUCCESS`
- [ ] JAR file generated: `bundle/target/com.mycompany.sample-app-1.0.0-SNAPSHOT.jar`
- [ ] Package ZIP generated: `package/target/com.mycompany.sample-app-1.0.0-SNAPSHOT.zip`
- [ ] No compilation errors in Maven output
- [ ] No missing dependency errors

**Red flag**: A successful `npm run build` but failed `mvn clean install` usually means the `pom.xml` frontend-maven-plugin config is out of sync or a Java backend issue — check Maven output carefully.

